John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have a number of academic successes, and this continues in 2018 with other excellent test results. Individual and group successes in sports, art, music and other community activities only underline this.
The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) represents more than 30,000 students across Scotland and strives to provide the best possible level of service to its students and parents.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they choose, and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement individually tailored school curricula, we observe that modern languages are still popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language they understand, it goes straight to their head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is a significant observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year's tests show that languages are at the top of the tables, with no higher level of success than independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language achieved the best grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that the highest grade A reached 72 percent of Mandarin students, 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by students are as important in the curricula of independent and other schools as STEM subjects (science, technology, technical fields and mathematics).
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 showed that, for reasons that employers cite as problems in filling vacancies, 17 percent of them do not have sufficient language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job opportunities require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalised world.
Whatever career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have the real advantage in the future that you have such a lifelong skill.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages will automatically gain an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, with the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, specifically 15%, being French.
That is why it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children learn more languages, especially languages of developing economies, they will have a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, every school is different in the way it teaches languages.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in view of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child is interested in, he will always have in independent schools a choice of several languages with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that languages are essential to the country’s future in a global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
