Harvard students take part in a course designed to teach them enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to fight the growing culture of macho studies all night long when students are not sleeping and encouraged with caffeine.
Academics have found that students at the world’s most famous university are often helpless when it comes to the basics of self-care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you just telling me this now, in my last year?’
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was introduced for the first time this year, explains to students basic information about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce a course after finding that students were really, really sleepless during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part is a picture of student dormitories where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleep habits.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
However, we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride in “studying all night” still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of lack of sleep is also growing.
Getting enough quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said — even to prevent it from happening because sleep deprivation switches the brain into starvation mode, so a person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student in chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes took last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push the whole course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
