Red tide update: Concentrations are declining in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota counties
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission points to a total drop in concentrations of the red tide in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, stains of flowering water are now reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – this indicates a decreasing concentration.
The blooming water of the red tide has a range of about 130 miles of coastline from the northern district of Pinellas to the southern district of Lee.
Spots were observed about 10 miles off the coast in Hillsborough County, but last week it was already relatively fewer places.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, medium concentrations were reported at the coast or on the high seas at the district of Pinellas. In the district of Hillsborough, low to high concentrations were observed at the high seas, lowest to high concentrations at the district of Manatee, lowest to high concentrations at the high seas, and highest concentrations at the high seas.
Respiratory irritation continues to occur in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Irritation of the airways was not reported in northwest Florida last week.
